The phosphorus cycle involves weathering
rocks releasing phosphate ( ) PO 3−
4 into soil
and groundwater. Producers take in phosphate,
which is incorporated into biological molecules;
consumers eat producers, transferring
phosphate to animals. Phosphorus returns
to the soil via decomposition of biomass, or
excretion. Phosphate can also be incorporated
back into the environment via decomposition
of decaying organic matter.

including nitrogen fixation, assimilation, 
ammonification, nitrification, and denitrification. 
These steps are performed by microorganisms
in the soil. The largest reservoir of nitrogen is
the atmosphere. In nitrogen fixation, nitrogen 
gas ( ) N2 is fixed into ammonia ( ) NH3 , which
ionizes to ammonium (NH ) +
4 by acquiring
hydrogen ions from the soil solution.

organisms as carbohydrates and back into the
atmosphere as carbon dioxide ( ) CO2 .

carbon cycle can be simplified into four 
parts: photosynthesis, cellular respiration,
decomposition, and combustion.

5F8D9F064348482A8702F83D288B7A6F.description:
Disruptions to the cell cycle may result in
cancer or apoptosis (programmed cell death).

E3A12181ADA147829D1BC4BB454E6C20.description:
Describe the effects of 
disruptions to the cell cycle
on the cell or organism.

29E081A6057548C3A02A3DFD699E61FB.description: Interactions between cyclins and cyclindependent kinases control the cell cycle.

9B80E4DF533A4346A1FCC417DBC74478.description:
A number of internal controls or checkpoints
regulate progression through the cell cycle.

6F9862FE9DF94C9BA4085395DAE3941C.description:
Describe the role of
checkpoints in regulating the
cell cycle.

2BC0E158F2654B4B8C8C631369EF6790.description:
Information Storage and Transmission: Living systems store, retrieve, transmit, and
respond to information essential to life processes.

2F3A5B8ED8964BD887D13A3DC29337F7.description:
Cytokinesis: A cleavage furrow forms in 
animal cells or a cell plate forms in plant
cells, resulting in two new daughter cells.

51D3904D86D24BF387CF0E214A671A0A.description:
Telophase: Mitotic spindle breaks down, 
a new nuclear envelope develops, and
then the cytoplasm divides.

70F76556409C4D7B93C19CBC2C8FAD40.description:
Anaphase: Paired sister chromatids 
separate as spindle fibers pull 
chromatids toward poles.

3487BD6D7C4B41BEAEE8C1CBC56A05CF.description:
Metaphase: Spindle fibers align 
chromosomes along the equator of the
cell.

5A1BDDD45B1646BFB86EE855C46336BB.description:
Prophase: Sister chromatids condense, 
mitotic spindle begins to form, and
centrosomes move to opposite poles of
the cell.

4F5A947FAD7F4962A6CB58D563B1D683.description:
Mitosis occurs in sequential steps 
(prophase, metaphase, anaphase,
telophase) and alternates with
interphase in the cell cycle.

48BD483830CF441E85E76C793D31FA3D.description:
Mitosis plays a role in growth, tissue 
repair, and asexual reproduction.

793B037D0DC24184BE4C85AD152E4E64.description:
Mitosis is a process that ensures the transfer
of a complete genome from a parent cell to
two genetically identical daughter cells in
eukaryotes.

24BA4A580DC3473CBC7AEB1F00403AA0.description:
Explain how mitosis results
in the transmission of
chromosomes from one
generation of cells to the 
next.

0365E6303C184AD19FC80BF9C4B0E21A.description:
Nondividing cells may exit the cell cycle
or be held at a particular stage in the cell
cycle.

E317C121B90B4840946DEAF77221E227.description:
A cell can enter a stage (G0) in which it no
longer divides, but it can reenter the cell
cycle in response to appropriate cues.

ECCC64B34A2C407E84DF569DD15142DC.description:
G2 phase: Protein synthesis occurs,
ATP is produced in large quantities, and
centrosomes replicate.

FE9A374645B24C60964CD5DFBA930CE6.description:
S phase: DNA is in the form of chromatin
and replicates to form two sister
chromatids connected at a centromere.

80F8AE9EC59F49FB8ED9C0CCA246612B.description:
G1 phase: The cell is metabolically active,
duplicating organelles and cytosolic
components.

792DD7231E7D4CA58327CD3597D5D7F1.description:
The cell cycle consists of sequential
stages of interphase (G1, S, G2), mitosis,
and cytokinesis.

FF6AB66B1FE14794998B3CD9CF6181AD.description:
The cell cycle is a highly regulated series
of events that controls the growth and
reproduction of eukaryotic cells.

1BCBFFA2E7DB48D6A480CF6AB2F379EA.description:
Describe the events that
occur in the cell cycle.

6B76E75AEDB946D7B5167D2F5051E5E1.description:
Information Storage and Transmission: Living systems store, retrieve, transmit, and
respond to information essential to life processes.

316700A3304A4E609E0842D27EB7BF5A.description:
Positive feedback mechanisms amplify
responses and processes in biological
organisms. The variable initiating the
response is moved further away from the
initial set point. Amplification occurs when 
the stimulus is further intensified, which, 
in turn, initiates an additional response
that produces system change.

2025E062799A4F51A7C540DFEF84EF8D.description:
Negative feedback mechanisms
maintain homeostasis by reducing the
initial stimulus to regulate physiological
processes. If a system is perturbed
or disrupted, negative feedback
mechanisms return the system back to its
target set point. These processes operate
at the molecular, cellular, and organismal
levels.

27D87731BDC94409A8FB87D3F6CDC485.description:
Organisms use feedback mechanisms
to maintain their internal environments in
response to internal and external changes.

E0F08B5DC910494FBF34E767374A63B6.description:
Explain how positive and
negative feedback helps
maintain homeostasis.

50945640ADA74D1A97927B3A3259EC92.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

E07557C861CC4AEABDEC80538E31C8FD.description:
Chemicals that interact with any component of
the signaling pathway may activate or inhibit
the pathway.

4EE5701910BE42929253C87B66F2A0A6.description:
Changes in signal transduction pathways
can alter cellular responses. Mutations in
any domain of the receptor protein or in any
component of the signaling pathway may
affect the downstream components by altering 
the subsequent transduction of the signal.

82A74E999E494AF582EEFBB1B3CDD4B7.description:
Explain how a change in the
structure of any signaling
molecule affects the activity 
of the signaling pathway.

915D6BC4CD1D4401AAB8179DDD1585CC.description:
Signal transduction may result in changes in
gene expressions and cell function, which may
alter phenotype or result in programmed cell
death (apoptosis).

A9417006D67645E3B11D990AB6FCB229.description:
Describe the different types 
of cellular responses elicited
by a signal transduction
pathway.

F2DDCBD63F024445B33FC4FE49DD5787.description:
Information Storage and Transmission: Living systems store, retrieve, transmit, and
respond to information essential to life processes.

ECF7FAF0361E43F9B3EC7C1AF201A12C.description:
The binding of ligands to ligand-gated 
channels can cause the channel to open
or close.

CD60C5720B1D43D980FA954E82AAD0B1.description:
Hormones are an example of a signaling
messenger that can travel long distances
in the bloodstream.

1AC8A7540D5F4FF0B995650AA86EFC47.description:
Enzymes and second messengers such 
as cyclic AMP (cAMP) relay and amplify
the intracellular signal.

0E25E62414C448C8AB2DB3A5887B0B5A.description:
After the ligand binds, the intracellular
domain of a receptor protein changes
shape, initiating transduction of the signal.

71464FF69B4342AAB5D4CA7D554ABB12.description:
Signaling cascades relay signals from
receptors to cell targets, often amplifying the
incoming signals, resulting in the appropriate
responses by the cell. Responses could include
cell growth, secretion of molecules, or gene
expression.

6425835A3DA346B69701630AC0E1C90D.description:
Receptors may be located on the surface
of a target cell or in the cytoplasm or
nucleus of the target cell.

ED0C7D92CB4748299CF900CFA6DD79DD.description:
G protein-coupled receptors are 
an example of a receptor protein in
eukaryotes.

C15519AAD3CC41D5950A02FB8CE322A3.description:
The ligand-binding domain of a 
receptor recognizes a specific chemical 
messenger, which can be a peptide
(protein) or a small molecule.

BB7B4BECE12B47959B63BAB8C97190EB.description:
Signaling begins with the recognition of a
chemical messenger—a ligand—by a receptor 
protein in a target cell.

9CB0890A66454EFFB27509D52BE2354A.description:
Describe the role of
components of a signal
transduction pathway
in producing a cellular
response.

EC9C5D7BC5C04C62913185E5D477B2C0.description:
Many signal transduction pathways
include protein modifications and involve 
phosphorylation cascades.

058A60F1E0C24EF88A20F69DF70B3D12.description:
Signal transduction pathways link signal
receptions with cellular responses.

C79DD04914AE4542A922CBF5F0358161.description:
Describe the components
of a signal transduction
pathway.

9CC258102D414B99886ACA2D9DA18049.description:
Information Storage and Transmission: Living systems store, retrieve, transmit, and
respond to information essential to life processes.

8297CD55099D4646A90D5F6BFB474F4A.description:
Signals released by one cell type can travel
long distances to target cells of another type.

D21D9859CA244AAB9221B8BC964F715A.description:
Cells communicate over short distances by
using local regulators that target cells in the
vicinity of the signal-emitting cell.

FEC2AFC58A2F44A58945748BCA1C8665.description:
Explain how cells
communicate with one
another over short and long
distances.

FF35E38404EF41A3B4EA9A68199E2346.description:
Cells communicate with one another through
direct contact with other cells or from a
distance via chemical signaling.

EAAD46BB535C44809285089050C55DB1.description:
Describe the ways that cells
can communicate with one
another.

DBE6F1F03E8442D8A1BB4C1246833FFB.description:
Information Storage and Transmission: Living systems store, retrieve, transmit, and
respond to information essential to life processes.

CEEB1E2D23C04E6C89571B72E95C13D9.description:
Fermentation allows glycolysis to proceed in
the absence of oxygen and produces organic
molecules such as alcohol and lactic acid.

5E9DAB464F084C09A56D077D7D5474CC.description:
When electrons are transferred between
molecules in a sequence of reactions as they
pass through the ETC, an electrochemical
gradient of protons (hydrogen ions) across the
inner mitochondrial membrane is established.
The pH inside the mitochondrial matrix is higher
than in the intermembrane space.

A9438462371B4F17AA3FF1E08326DA12.description:
Electrons extracted in glycolysis and Krebs
cycle reactions are transferred by NADH and
FADH2 to the ETC in the inner mitochondrial
membrane.

4841D86092484580A6FB340066F92AC6.description:
The Krebs cycle takes place in the mitochondrial
matrix. During the Krebs cycle, carbon dioxide
is released from organic intermediates, ATP is
synthesized from ADP and inorganic phosphate, 
and electrons are transferred by the coenzymes  + NAD and FAD.

36DC4B57DA15498A99B65C9A3965000F.description:
Pyruvate is transported from the cytosol to the
mitochondrion where oxidation occurs. This
process releases electrons during the Krebs
(citric acid) cycle, reducing NAD+
 to NADH and
FAD to FADH2, and releasing CO2 .

F863F0701472446899D4C3A651048EA2.description:
Glycolysis is a biochemical pathway that
releases the energy in glucose molecules to
form ATP (from ADP and inorganic phosphate),
NADH (from NAD+
), and pyruvate.

5BC5523C84034FD197F5F134B880AB1C.description:
Explain how cells obtain
energy from biological
macromolecules in order to
power cellular functions.

7BB2682A127948E2A35AFDAF6DE22E4C.description:
In aerobic cellular respiration, decoupling
oxidative phosphorylation from electron
transport generates heat. This heat can
be used by endothermic organisms to
regulate body temperature.

188485E3AFFE468FBDFA50DC77094C5E.description:
The flow of protons back through 
membrane-bound ATP synthase by 
chemiosmosis drives the formation of ATP
from ADP and inorganic phosphate. This
is known as oxidative phosphorylation in
aerobic cellular respiration.

558A6AF8790A442485EFB99D0B2D8F82.description:
The transfer of electrons, through the
ETC, is accompanied by the formation
of a proton gradient across the inner
mitochondrial membrane, with the
membrane(s) separating a region of
high proton concentration outside the
membrane from a region of low proton
concentration inside the membrane. The
folding of the inner membrane increases
the surface area, which allows for more
ATP to be synthesized. In prokaryotes, 
the passage of electrons is accompanied
by the movement of protons across the
plasma membrane.

CD44EAABAB934B72A3D5AE53CD5399B0.description:
In cellular respiration, electrons delivered
by NADH and FADH2 are passed to a
series of electron acceptors as they move
toward the terminal electron acceptor,
oxygen. Aerobic prokaryotes use
oxygen as a terminal electron acceptor,
while anaerobic prokaryotes use other
molecules.

27DC2E648F9D4506B346F262EF442B63.description:
The ETC transfers electrons in a series of
oxidation-reduction reactions that establish an 
electrochemical gradient across membranes.

186753AE274141DCA1B70F5557CE6F3B.description:
Aerobic cellular respiration in eukaryotes
involves a series of coordinated enzymecatalyzed reactions that capture energy from 
biological macromolecules.

7A866225729E45D699718642F9440A53.description:
Cellular respiration uses energy from biological
macromolecules to synthesize ATP. Respiration 
and fermentation are characteristic of all forms
of life.

E04AEBFD4C0A4CEA9B46BCDF6EB596FB.description:
Describe the processes
and structural features
of mitochondria that
allow organisms to use
energy stored in biological
macromolecules.

69D5AB53B370437EB0FB01C90E936C78.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

9CE5D8DC65974A9EA7E5FACF33E585B8.description:
The energy captured in the light reactions
and transferred to ATP and NADPH powers
the production of carbohydrates from carbon
dioxide in the Calvin cycle. This occurs in the
stroma of the chloroplast.

087CC75B634545C7B8D95524952E47A9.description:
The formation of the proton gradient is
linked to the synthesis of ATP from ADP and
inorganic phosphate via ATP synthase. The
flow of protons back through membranebound ATP synthase by chemiosmosis
drives the formation of ATP from ADP
and inorganic phosphate; this is known as
photophosphorylation.

C19FDC2DB93647A79AA2D482E3CD41E5.description:
When electrons are transferred between
molecules in a series of oxidation/reduction
reactions as they pass through the ETC, an
electrochemical gradient of protons (hydrogen
ions) is established across the thylakoid
membrane. The membrane separates a
region of low proton concentration outside
the thylakoid membrane from a region of high
proton concentration inside the thylakoid
membrane.

3D4F46B5E80645E2B3B952748975E374.description:
Photosystems I and II are embedded in the
thylakoid membranes of chloroplasts and are
connected by the transfer of electrons through
an ETC.

6C495C0DA0C54028828B5299F6892F09.description:
During photosynthesis, chlorophylls absorb
energy from light, boosting electrons to a
higher energy level in photosystems I and
II. Water then splits, supplying electrons to
replace those lost from photosystem II.

C0B9BD46A16C4F3E9D5D278B18B7DC5C.description:
Electron transport chain (ETC) reactions
occur in chloroplasts, in mitochondria, and 
across prokaryotic plasma membranes. In
photosynthesis, electrons that pass through
the thylakoid membrane are picked up and
ultimately transferred to NADP+ reducing it to
NADPH in photosystem I.

9A14C4D1E4F54E13B7A8C76314327990.description:
Explain how cells capture
energy from light and transfer
it to biological molecules for
storage and use.

A03D90984AB84128A14DE999BC21082B.description:
The light reactions of photosynthesis in
eukaryotes involve a series of coordinated
reaction pathways that capture energy
present in light to yield ATP and NADPH, which
power the production of organic molecules
in the Calvin cycle. This provides energy for
metabolic processes.

73034AD42A8E478C9584FF042575941B.description:
Thylakoids are organized in stacks 
called grana. The light reactions of
photosynthesis occur in the grana.

15DA931C0A434361AC29F7F583763BF7.description:
The thylakoid membranes contain
chlorophyll pigments organized into 
two photosystems, as well as electron
transport proteins.

D9565595E3784CD797B2091DAE26A7DF.description:
The stroma is the fluid within the inner 
chloroplast membrane and outside the
thylakoid. The carbon fixation (Calvin 
cycle) reactions of photosynthesis occur
in the stroma.

68DB1403D79F46F3AB938A3CBE975778.description:
Stroma and thylakoids are found within the
chloroplast.

1EFE2390FBC045D196C54DE36B3E3021.description:
Prokaryotic photosynthetic pathways
were the foundation of eukaryotic
photosynthesis.

0F28DBF595F0443B98981A53552A33DB.description:
Scientific evidence supports the 
claim that prokaryotic (cyanobacterial)
photosynthesis was responsible for the
production of an oxygenated atmosphere.

23B08676DD594834873DF9E8BE75A17F.description:
Photosynthesis first evolved in 
prokaryotic organisms.

3B3BF4DD092C4AC184E464E4EDF4DAB4.description:
Photosynthetic organisms capture energy
from the sun and produce sugars that can
be used in biological processes or stored.

9C4CD55243044A05B469BF219716F5C7.description:
Photosynthesis is the series of reactions
that use carbon dioxide ( ) CO2 , water ( ) H O2 ,
and light energy to make carbohydrates and
oxygen ( ) O2 .

A8C4524D1FED4731B91E70C8750FADBA.description:
Describe the photosynthetic
processes and structural
features of the chloroplast
that allow organisms to
capture and store energy.

357F1F99485044F1893BDA7791EE3C49.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

98304CBD025D40C58EAE7EC8639F35F8.description:
Core metabolic pathways (e.g., glycolysis,
oxidative phosphorylation) are conserved
across all currently recognized domains 
(Archaea, Bacteria, and Eukarya).

6F0FEC81519643BDB08C115F0E235A9A.description:
Explain how shared,
conserved, and fundamental
processes and features
support the concept of
common ancestry for all
organisms.

48DBF2A952B249B0BD2F201294819C5A.description:
Energy-related pathways in biological systems 
are sequential to allow for a more controlled
transfer of energy. A product of a reaction in a
metabolic pathway is typically the reactant for
the subsequent step in the pathway.

38F927BDEBC9495CA20019D15D2BC82F.description:
Significant loss of order or energy flow 
results in death.

90078B2D4819449FAA75CBE4FA2359F8.description:
Cellular processes that release energy
may be coupled with cellular processes
that require energy.

43C435E314B940B0AC45CEE13AAFB820.description:
Energy input must exceed energy loss
to maintain order and to power cellular
processes.

A100BB5D637E48558BAB45F29A762793.description:
Life requires a highly ordered system and
does not violate the first and second laws of 
thermodynamics.

6F02CEC6C1C548098250145DEA5E4DD9.description: All living systems require an input of energy.

DBAAB50F6501465AA38AFAAABE652130.description:
Describe the role of energy in
living organisms.

3B923AE6B36741BEB59D72163B7E5FCA.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

07291DAC69904A088E178582255C7002.description:
Competitive inhibitor molecules can bind
reversibly to the active site of the enzyme. 
Noncompetitive inhibitors can bind to allosteric
sites, changing the activity of the enzyme.

B8555D86743B4F45B5B58E0C7C035B56.description:
Higher environmental temperatures increase
the average speed of movement of molecules
in a solution, increasing the frequency of
collisions between enzymes and substrates 
and therefore increasing the rate of reaction
until the optimal temperature is achieved.

2C9AB47B7AC54AD084EF81F2E272D82D.description:
The relative concentrations of substrates
and products determine how efficiently an 
enzymatic reaction proceeds.

A1250F08DBE44200AA754E81BD27CB84.description:
Explain how the cellular
environment affects enzyme 
activity.

564942DAE00C4A1997E553BAC4C588C1.description:
In some cases, enzyme denaturation is 
reversible, allowing the enzyme to regain 
activity

7ECB2909CBB446F18DC47109FCCF8A7F.description:
Environmental temperatures and pH
outside the optimal range for a given
enzyme will cause changes to its 
structure (by disrupting the hydrogen
bonds), altering the efficiency with which 
it catalyzes reactions.

CBE32D03D31440E594F63E91D3FC3D7F.description:
Denaturation of proteins, such as
enzymes, occurs when the protein 
structure is disrupted by a change
in temperature, pH, or chemical
environment, eliminating the ability to
catalyze reactions.

C8D31CF4499C4A48AEEB4F512910BDF4.description:
Change to the molecular structure of a
component in an enzymatic system may result 
in a change to its function or efficiency.

B17D692B4CC94A5789596CEB4D8B22F8.description:
Explain how changes to the
structure of an enzyme may 
affect its function.

70725E8FEF264BD6BF831753FD5F0DAB.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

6A9B103A552F41EEA631AED7144C284A.description:
For an enzyme-mediated chemical reaction to 
occur, the shape and charge of the substrate
must be compatible with the active site of the
enzyme. This is illustrated by the enzymesubstrate complex model.

84149E89F67B4EC4B89D6E4F1CF1CE2B.description:
The structure and function of enzymes 
contribute to the regulation of biological
processes. Enzymes are proteins that are 
biological catalysts that facilitate chemical
reactions in cells by lowering the activation
energy

410291435BED4C0487ECBB30F73F77DB.description:
Explain how enzymes 
affect the rate of biological 
reactions.

8D70A098CF6B4DBDB7F81F4F9B64F20D.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

A0659713E88C4088994262293EFBA7A3.description:
Eukaryotic cells maintain internal membranes
that partition the cell into specialized regions.

55C404408F03426381407B1E357CC82A.description:
Prokaryotes typically lack internal membranebound organelles but have internal regions with
specialized structures and functions.

57293CCB7E3644079592DB9449209E0C.description:
Membrane-bound organelles such as 
mitochondria and chloroplasts evolved
from once free-living prokaryotic cells via 
endosymbiosis.

A0A8F8F46781410780D16B68BDA1D76F.description:
Describe similarities
and/or differences in 
compartmentalization 
between prokaryotic and
eukaryotic cells.

2C86125EA2304F1081CE8667B9EA1F0E.description: Evolution: The process of evolution drives the diversity and unity of life.

81276FE775484F1A9B71D8047AA199D6.description:
Internal membranes facilitate cellular
processes by minimizing competing 
interactions and by increasing the surface area
where reactions can occur.

3E4477D07FF34A6CABEFFA9FB2F113D3.description:
Explain how internal
membranes and membranebound organelles contribute
to compartmentalization of 
eukaryotic cell functions.

40022644B6CD4A7BBBACB4ACAB7D7530.description:
Membranes and membrane-bound organelles 
in eukaryotic cells compartmentalize 
intracellular metabolic processes and specific 
enzymatic reactions.

1F5118B644E84C58BA0D3285174D0B96.description:
Describe the membranebound structures of the
eukaryotic cell.

5E6A83018D8C4DC69E1879E779AAB317.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

ACA8C33A640E4191B2C637DD1775B24F.description:
The + + Na /K pump and ATPase contribute
to the maintenance of the membrane
potential.

29B4E71264014C9BBA689BA3835082FE.description:
Membrane proteins are necessary for
active transport.

E8944290EEC34704B6A5E2369C14451B.description:
Metabolic energy (such as that from ATP) is
required for active transport of molecules and
ions across the membrane and to establish and
maintain electrochemical gradients.

1668604E51324C9AAD97A1CF8D6ED4B5.description:
Describe the processes
that allow ions and other
molecules to move across
membranes.

3C65FE0C8D1448848C1A8D93F2F3F8F2.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

1420A1B440934805978690307783BE07.description:
Osmoregulation maintains water balance
and allows organisms to control their internal
solute composition and water potential. Water
moves from regions of low osmolarity or solute
concentration to regions of high osmolarity or
solute concentration.

942CA8D80AEB4FA5A599A9E6C237D3D6.description:
Growth and homeostasis are maintained by
the constant movement of molecules across
membranes.

7BD40D483671473DB31B2AF1AD35D0AC.description:
Explain how osmoregulatory
mechanisms contribute to
the health and survival of
organisms.

932AB59F7E37490CBD31AE9AC6D944A1.description:
External environments can be hypotonic,
hypertonic, or isotonic to internal environments
of cells. Movement of water can also be
described as moving from hypotonic to
hypertonic regions. Water moves by osmosis
from regions of high water potential to regions
of low water potential.

225803D673D84FF4A45ADBB3DA96FEAE.description:
Explain how concentration
gradients affect the 
movement of molecules
across membranes.

D069986ED4C74C39BB420BEB4DF64998.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

5BD0026FEEAC4C3A8C845A924520F10F.description:
Aquaporins transport large quantities of water
across membranes.

458F6A74987C4A68ABE12F6F3821E8D9.description:
Facilitated diffusion enables the movement 
of large polar molecules through membranes
with no energy input. In this type of diffusion, 
substances move down the concentration
gradient.

8FE3AE9C0E3147F7906D0B2021F12DAB.description:
Charged ions, including Na+
 (sodium) and
K+
 (potassium), require channel proteins
to move through the membrane.

C59A5824333641B68CEC4EB722642F55.description:
Membranes may become polarized by the 
movement of ions across the membrane.

F6DA8DD9B8C44D96944C786E7DBCE715.description:
Facilitated diffusion requires transport or 
channel proteins to enable the movement of
charged ions across the membrane.

C0A85D06539C4455A419A2B6E8DE2B72.description:
Explain how the structure of
a molecule affects its ability 
to pass through the plasma
membrane.

C59E3395F72F4B51B19B4D4905E51905.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

B03D893843C346B7B4AC1F289BB2607F.description:
In exocytosis, internal vesicles release
material from cells by fusing with the
plasma membrane and secreting large
molecules from the cell.

B5A76C6C7B4E4ED7BC9827895E1BB834.description:
In endocytosis, the cell takes in large
molecules and particulate matter by folding
the plasma membrane in on itself and
forming new (small) vesicles that engulf
material from the external environment.

A59EA50DBCFA4B0486FF23C40CEF507D.description:
The processes of endocytosis and exocytosis
require energy to move large substances or large
amounts of substances into and out of cells.

9F23279D254A4549890459EA2F551243.description:
Describe the mechanisms
that organisms use to
transport large molecules
across the plasma
membrane.

44D5328C8AA84555B00C443A3780CB03.description:
Active transport requires the direct input of
energy to move molecules. In some cases, active
transport is utilized to move molecules from 
regions of low concentration to regions of high
concentration.

24C86C46BA124820829301A910B8BCB4.description:
Passive transport is the net movement of
molecules from regions of high concentration
to regions of low concentration without the
direct input of metabolic energy.

AAAC09D1530F4D579CBC55158D053375.description:
The selective permeability of membranes
allows for the formation of concentration
gradients of solutes across the membrane.

E8703BF10D5541A294B1786380FB4E08.description:
Describe the mechanisms
that organisms use to
maintain solute and water
balance.

9E954E8675CB4949818D09CC17AF3A43.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

856CBEB849064184BC31999215E54C9A.description:
Cell walls of Bacteria, Archaea, Fungi, and
plants provide a structural boundary as well as
a permeability barrier for some substances to
the internal or external cellular environments
and protection from osmotic lysis.

515C1414883C49B88C68AE74DE239F05.description:
Describe the role of the
cell wall in maintaining cell
structure and function.

6F669072AF8F4CCFA99BA54EA7B9F113.description:
The nonpolar hydrocarbon tails of
phospholipids prevent the movement of ions
and polar molecules across the membrane.
Small polar, uncharged molecules, like H O2 or
NH3 (ammonia), pass through the membrane in
small amounts.

CACE5E2ADF2240CC958DBBA765519F08.description:
Small nonpolar molecules, including N2, O2 ,
and CO2 , freely pass across the membrane.
Hydrophilic substances, such as large
polar molecules and ions, move across the
membrane through embedded channels and
transport proteins.

77EE20CF788445F5A9E8A12795920357.description:
Plasma membranes separate the internal
environment of the cell from the external
environment. Selective permeability is the
result of the plasma membrane having a
hydrophobic interior.

EDE12F213E1E4EFE9B18095219373D21.description:
Explain how the structure
of biological membranes
influences selective 
permeability.

9E74095FDD4049F491F4242605D12483.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

4C466DC3652F47BB9D01572D62548718.description:
Plasma membranes consist of a structural
framework of phospholipid molecules embedded
with proteins, steroids (such as cholesterol
in vertebrate animals), glycoproteins, and
glycolipids. All of these can move around the
surface of the cell within the membrane, as
illustrated by the fluid mosaic model.

8F3DE2454DE94276A20ABD64E44BB9AA.description:
Describe the fluid mosaic 
model of cell membranes.

169A7D8500FE455D809038FA25D05867.description:
Hydrophobic regions of proteins make up
the protein surface that interacts with the
fatty acids in the interior membrane.

1BDC34E1C6654464BC8B942CE5CE8B63.description:
Hydrophilic regions of the proteins are
either inside the interior of the protein or
exposed to the cytosol (cytoplasm).

3023E2368AE842698EE4E23ABE222E63.description:
Embedded proteins can be hydrophilic (with
charged and polar side groups), hydrophobic
(with nonpolar side groups), or both.

305DFC072621498686623F914717A56B.description:
Phospholipids have both hydrophilic and
hydrophobic regions. The polar hydrophilic
phosphate regions of the phospholipids
are oriented toward the aqueous external
or internal environment, while the nonpolar
hydrophobic fatty acid regions face each other
within the interior of the membrane.

F9CE9BAB39FA463395EAF36CF1BCF3BD.description:
Describe the roles of each of
the components of the cell
membrane in maintaining the
internal environment of the
cell.

C2AF3D0C7D0842099AAEFFE8DFB3AA1D.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

ED0AE5AD3E924D1AA558180A56A1C645.description:
There is a relationship between metabolic
rate per unit body mass and the size of 
multicellular organisms; typically, the
smaller the organism, the higher the
metabolic rate per unit body mass.

7AEE6498C8DD499494DA4EE1E82FD65E.description:
As organisms increase in size, their 
surface area-to-volume ratio decreases, 
affecting properties like rate of heat 
exchange with the environment.
Smaller amounts of mass exchange
proportionally more heat with the ambient
environment than do larger masses. As
mass increases, both the surface areato-volume ratio and the rate of heat 
exchange decrease.

DC1C3AE917084F619D4F0CE8D8FCB6F7.description:
More complex cellular structures (e.g.,
membrane folds) are necessary to
adequately exchange materials with the
environment.

B888C4F1359847D6A93D6B623DF62952.description:
As cells increase in volume, the surface
area-to-volume ratio decreases and the 
demand for internal resources increases.

20742DB822E94FFE90B4472C2D706819.description:
The surface area-to-volume ratio can 
restrict cell size and shape. Smaller 
cells typically have a higher surface
area-to-volume ratio as well as a more 
efficient exchange of materials with the 
environment than do larger cells.

B64755DA25F848888B3B5DE1DB437C09.description:
The surface area of the plasma membrane
must be large enough to adequately exchange
materials.

38FD9DFAB2E4420488C8225AA791ED8E.description:
Surface area-to-volume ratios affect the ability 
of a biological system to obtain necessary
nutrients, eliminate waste products, acquire
or dissipate thermal energy, and otherwise
exchange chemicals and energy with the
environment.

E0DEF6CA213E449189C797F9F4920ABA.description:
Explain the effect of surface 
area-to-volume ratios on 
the exchange of materials
between cells or organisms
and the environment.

E13DEC44A1C34912B280732958E5C26D.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

7780BB5385584984B44CA35836EBA22B.description:
Chloroplasts are specialized organelles that 
are found in plants and photosynthetic algae.
Chloroplasts contain a double membrane and
serve as the location for photosynthesis.

9FCB74490921410AA0BBE837072A53CB.description:
In animal cells, vacuoles are smaller in
size, are more plentiful than in plant cells, 
and store cellular materials.

198EA450B0F546949DD9F49628C0B2ED.description:
In plant cells, a specialized large vacuole 
maintains turgor pressure through
nutrient and water storage.

0778A6EDAAFC4F12ACD387CD65B4E978.description:
Vacuoles are membrane-bound sacs that play 
many different roles.

1CF9DF16BBCF4F7D8412080302951126.description:
Lysosomes are membrane-enclosed sacs 
that contain hydrolytic enzymes that digest 
material. Lysosomes also play a role in
programmed cell death (apoptosis).

5D81AC3A5CA64BA599C8186DE228A6A0.description:
Mitochondria have a double membrane
that provides compartments for different 
metabolic reactions involved in aerobic
cellular respiration. The outer membrane is
smooth, while the inner membrane is highly
convoluted, forming folds that enable ATP to be
synthesized more efficiently.

5EB6942ED58F4911B905F4E7BBD8D1BD.description:
Correctly folding and chemically
modifying newly synthesized cellular 
products

25FCFE7A165A416BA136EA03BABA6437.description:
The Golgi complex is a membrane-bound 
structure that consists of a series of flattened 
membrane sacs. Functions of the Golgi include:

C2E37D1779A74CB5A7C700C409883274.description:
Smooth ER functions include the
detoxification of cells and lipid synthesis.

07CB172CDB4C445C8E101208406355EB.description:
Rough ER is associated with membranebound ribosomes, allows for the 
compartmentalization of cells, and helps 
carry out protein synthesis.

BE9EAB8E8624473BADE5B2D0ED62782A.description:
Endoplasmic reticulum provides mechanical
support by helping cells maintain shape and
plays a role in intracellular transport.

693E9D866BC94CDCB17A53FCB7DC4BE0.description:
The endomembrane system consists of
a group of membrane-bound organelles 
and subcellular components (endoplasmic
reticulum (ER), Golgi complex, lysosomes,
vacuoles and transport vesicles, the nuclear
envelope, and the plasma membrane) that
work together to modify, package, and
transport polysaccharides, lipids, and proteins
intercellularly.

A228D67469D44C468FD70072793C6B2D.description:
Ribosomes are comprised of ribosomal RNA
(rRNA) and protein. These non-membrane, 
subcellular structures are found in cells in all
forms of life and reflect the common ancestry 
in all known life. Ribosomes synthesize 
proteins according to messenger RNA (mRNA)
sequences.

03DDEE1C1A1648DBAEAF08B3B73DD61F.description:
Explain how the structure
and function of subcellular
components and organelles
contribute to the function of
cells.

CDAB4FC970814AC09575A36D9122C640.description:
Systems Interactions: Biological systems interact, and these systems and their
interactions exhibit complex properties.

85A844F6D9124F048533AF2E6AD7E3EA.description:
The quaternary structure arises from
interactions between multiple polypeptides. All
four levels of a protein structure determine the
function of a protein.

2FBE1F6DAF6E419D82B35D95274ACA58.description:
The three-dimensional shape of the tertiary 
structure of a protein results from the
formation of hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic
interactions, ionic interactions, or disulfide 
bridges.

F5A8E5AA04B94C52BC42C6B0A06B941E.description:
Secondary structures of proteins are made
through the local folding that forms from
interactions between atoms of the polypeptide
backbone of the amino acid chain. Hydrogen
bonding forms shapes such as alpha-helices 
and beta-pleated sheets.

12338F4C547B49B486518393E765B427.description:
The specific sequence of amino acids in 
proteins determines the primary structure of a
polypeptide as well as the overall shape of the
protein.

CFD8753F25B347EC9DD1BC160B6E4825.description:
Amino acids are composed of a central
carbon atom with a hydrogen atom, a carboxyl
group, an amine group, and a variable R group
covalently bound to it. The R group of an amino
acid can be categorized by three possible 
chemical properties: hydrophobic/nonpolar,
hydrophilic/polar, or ionic. The interactions of
these R groups determine the structure and
function of that region of the protein.

F2432AA08E6A4785A8D45543DF98869E.description:
Proteins comprise linear chains of amino
acids connected by the formation of covalent
(peptide) bonds that form between a carboxyl
group (−COOH) of one amino acid and an amine
group ( N− H )2 of the next amino acid, resulting
in a growing peptide chain.

5854E06A43954CC9B67D1587F0E686E9.description:
Describe the structure and
function of proteins.

75F5CB892F444D619F516DA8B6830ED8.description:
Information Storage and Transmission: Living systems store, retrieve, transmit, and
respond to information essential to life processes.

05B8876D7D1641D78C68A4C92B74F00B.description:
DNA is typically double stranded, while
RNA is typically single stranded.

824168B8E1F14DC9A9207E05E76D206A.description:
DNA contains the nitrogenous base
thymine, and RNA contains the
nitrogenous base uracil.

5EF83DD7E1BB4687AEC885E33B7D2605.description:
DNA contains the sugar deoxyribose, and
RNA contains the sugar ribose.

32D1E42B01BF413996CCF691E7FFEAD2.description:
Structural differences between DNA and RNA 
include:

9053C364EF6A483EB51D824901C994FA.description:
DNA is structured as an antiparallel double
helix, with two strands of nucleotides running
in opposite 5’ to 3’ orientation. In DNA, adenine
nucleotides pair with thymine nucleotides
via hydrogen bonds (A-T), and cytosine 
nucleotides pair with guanine nucleotides via
hydrogen bonds (C-G). In RNA, adenine pairs 
with uracil (A-U).

0C3EA274038547C280D029D774FAE548.description:
Nucleic acids have a linear sequence of
nucleotides that have ends, defined by the 
3’ (three prime) hydroxyl and 5’ (five prime) 
phosphates of the sugar in the nucleotide.
During nucleic acid synthesis, nucleotides
are added to the 3’ end of the growing strand,
resulting in the formation of covalent bonds
between nucleotides.

69A2888B8ED54371B6435626B570B019.description:
In nucleic acids (DNA and RNA), biological
information is encoded in sequences of
nucleotide monomers. Each nucleotide has the
following structural components: a five-carbon 
sugar (deoxyribose or ribose), a phosphate, and
a nitrogenous base (adenine, thymine, guanine,
cytosine, or uracil).

0064F09D0BFF47E19CAB4E1C6D11D6AF.description:
Describe the structure and
function of DNA and RNA.

9C227FD53F184609993C4952BFF37140.description:
Information Storage and Transmission: Living systems store, retrieve, transmit, and
respond to information essential to life processes.

8370E9F0594744B1B1D1A44B0E1817C3.description:
Phospholipids group together to form
the lipid bilayers found in plasma and cell
membranes.

CF9FAD809E81494AB5A8D27B2C933436.description:
Cholesterol provides essential structural
stability to animal cell membranes.

B57D5C6D533542DB9AD380190CD2CA30.description:
Steroids are hormones that support
physiological functions including growth
and development, energy metabolism,
and homeostasis.

FB96EB8CFB844DA6AD131416EC9919E8.description:
Fats provide energy storage and support
cell function. In some cases, they can also
provide insulation to help keep mammals
warm.

2B2EE24C290546EEA53938F5DB2C1652.description:
Lipids provide a variety of functions for
living organisms. Some examples of lipids
are fats, steroids including cholesterol, and
phospholipids.

4D7972F2912D45A0BB229D2B1C23507F.description:
The more unsaturated a lipid is, the more
liquid it is at room temperature.

657B20293AE243F4AF9867D7192980AB.description:
The more double bonds in a fatty acid tail,
the more unsaturated the lipid becomes.

531805E8AB0E4C53A76884A51582CBB7.description:
Unsaturated fatty acids contain at least
one double bond between carbon atoms,
which causes the carbon chain to kink.

11764DEE3B354E659B6D5F352A3CACEB.description:
Saturated fatty acids contain only single
bonds between carbon atoms.

7EFAC47C59AA4086BBBDC9F240FE95EB.description:
Lipids are typically nonpolar, hydrophobic
molecules whose structure and function are
derived from the way their subcomponents are
assembled. Fatty acids can be described as
either saturated or unsaturated.

61B3A18BD3034B3CB5FB8950B8165BA1.description:
Describe the structure and
function of lipids.

CE0EBA670C4E492EA60F21FB40D6DC66.description:
Systems Interactions: Biological systems interact, and these systems and their
interactions exhibit complex properties.

ED7C64224416433AA5FE8D3BB5CBDF1F.description:
Monosaccharides (simple sugars) are the
monomers for polysaccharides (complex
carbohydrates). These monomers are
connected by covalent bonds to form polymers
such as complex carbohydrates, which may be
linear or branched.

8EDBE90D4A8C44D9B88662B2AFC3C2E8.description:
Describe the structure and
function of carbohydrates.

5EF5CBB72FE642959E668AB9F510173D.description:
Systems Interactions: Biological systems interact, and these systems and their
interactions exhibit complex properties.

21DBDBB012A24093901522B9459A3472.description:
Dehydration synthesis occurs when two
smaller molecules are joined together through
covalent bonding. A hydrogen ion is removed
from one monomer and a hydroxyl group is
removed from the other. This causes the loss
of the equivalent of a water molecule from
the reactants and the connection of the two
remaining monomers. The connection of many
monomers is known as polymerization.

8F89548C28584678B3DCE7F10F4DCBA6.description:
Hydrolysis is a chemical reaction involving
the cleaving of covalent bonds. This type of
reaction breaks down molecules into smaller
molecules. When water is added to the bond
between monomers in a polymer, the bond
is broken. The hydrogen ion from a water
molecule is added to one monomer and the
hydroxyl group of the water molecule is added
to the other monomer, completing the reaction.

22D60B187B9D4680881AA165E59B66E0.description:
Describe the chemical
reactions that build and break
biological macromolecules.

01B9B385B9F340D4A0A596D4DA80612A.description:
Systems Interactions: Biological systems interact, and these systems and their
interactions exhibit complex properties.

338488B1C1284AB9B917BFFC2FFA3DC9.description:
Nitrogen is used in the building of nucleic
acids.

3AA1622FE9A24E34A717692D34E4B16D.description:
Phosphorus is used in the building of
phospholipids (a type of lipid) and nucleic
acids.

5C05E4D1F99F47F7BA9F1479AB1BDBCD.description: Sulfur is used in the building of proteins.

E09BE305053644AB8F7ACD2E088C2E7C.description:
Atoms and molecules from the environment
are necessary to build new molecules. Carbon,
hydrogen, and oxygen are the most prevalent
elements used to build biological molecules
such as carbohydrates, proteins, lipids, and
nucleic acids. Additionally:

B12C63C8138A41ECB8F3F116ECF3C966.description:
Describe the composition of
macromolecules required by
living organisms.

3BEA64445F3F47B8B5FF50A97E6D9B04.description:
Energetics: Biological systems use energy and molecular building blocks to grow,
reproduce, and maintain dynamic homeostasis.

F119F93729B34502BA314CDBC3D4AB1D.description:
The hydrogen bonds between adjacent polar
water molecules result in cohesion, adhesion,
and surface tension.

CDCABA14256F40AB92FBF147C6D58091.description:
Water has a high heat of vaporization, 
which allows for the evaporative cooling
of the surrounding environment. In living
organisms, this property allows for body
temperature to be maintained.

48515D4EBA52411A8CCFF45802A5BA00.description:
Water has a high specific heat capacity, 
which allows for the maintenance of
homeostatic body temperature within
living organisms.

883813C6216844BEA26FB1D09EFEAD1B.description:
Water has polarity, because of the formation of polar covalent bonds
between hydrogen and oxygen within
water molecules. This polarity contributes
to hydrogen bonding between and within
biological molecules.

9A0DC164D33B4255B7E1DAF7A97E3839.description:
Living systems depend on the properties of
water to sustain life.

Explain how the properties
of water that result from
its polarity and hydrogen
bonding affect its biological function.
